# React Best Practices

## Memoization

- Use `React.memo()` when a component receives stable props in a frequently re-rendered parent tree
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations (array filtering, sorting, aggregation)
- Use `useCallback` for callbacks passed as props to `React.memo()` children
- Do NOT memoize blindly — only when there is a structural or measurable reason
- Never pass inline object/array literals as props to memoized components

```tsx
// BAD — inline object defeats React.memo on Child
<Child style={{ color: 'red' }} />

// GOOD
const style = useMemo(() => ({ color: 'red' }), []);
<Child style={style} />
```

## Hooks

- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks named `use[Feature]` (e.g., `useChessGame`, `useAuth`)
- Never use `useEffect` for derived state — compute during render
- Prefer `useMemo` over `useEffect` + `setState` for computed values
- Keep `useEffect` dependencies minimal and explicit — no `// eslint-disable-next-line`

```tsx
// BAD
const [fullName, setFullName] = useState('');
useEffect(() => { setFullName(`${first} ${last}`); }, [first, last]);

// GOOD
const fullName = `${first} ${last}`;
```

## Component Patterns

- Prefer composition over prop drilling — use children, render props, or context
- Keep components focused — if a component handles more than one concern, split it
- Colocate related files (component, test, styles) in the same directory
- Use named exports, not default exports
- No `any` — strict TypeScript everywhere
- Prefer `interface` for component props, `type` for unions and utility types
